'''Denial of pregnancy''' (also called '''pregnancy denial''') is a rare form of [[denial]] exhibited by women to either the fact or the implications of their own [[pregnancy]]. One study found that women who denied their pregnancy represented 0.26% of all deliveries.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Friedman |first1=Susan Hatters |last2=Heneghan |first2=Amy |last3=Rosenthal |first3=Miriam |title=Characteristics of Women Who Deny or Conceal Pregnancy |journal=Psychosomatics |volume=48 |issue=2 |pages=117–22 |year=2007 |pmid=17329604 |doi=10.1176/appi.psy.48.2.117 }}</ref>   A later study cited that at 20 weeks gestation approximately 1 in 475 pregnant women denied their pregnancy, and said the proportion of cases persisting even until delivery is about 1 in 2500 refusing to acknowledge that they are pregnant.<ref name="pmid21725094">{{cite journal |vauthors=Jenkins A, Millar S, Robins J | title = Denial of pregnancy: a literature review and discussion of ethical and legal issues | journal = Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine | volume = 104 | issue = 7 | pages = 286–91 | date = July 2011 | pmid = 21725094 | doi = 10.1258/jrsm.2011.100376 | pmc=3128877}}</ref> 

==Psychotic denial==
This is a form of denial that is so extreme as to fall under the category of [[delusion]]. While physical symptoms of pregnancy do usually occur, they are sometimes misinterpreted by the woman. Some women interpret the sensation of something growing inside them as cancer, or a blood clot. Some women might believe fetal movements are their organs coming loose inside her body.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Miller |first1=Laura J. |chapter=Denial of Pregnancy |pages=81–104 |chapterurl={{Google books|i4XqOuxjzvIC|page=81|plainurl=yes}} |editor1-last=Spinelli |editor1-first=Margaret G. |year=2008 |title=Infanticide: Psychosocial and Legal Perspectives on Mothers Who Kill |publisher=American Psychiatric |isbn=978-1-58562-754-7 }}</ref> During the psychotic denial pregnancy, women tend to hide their pregnancy from everyone and put their fetus at a high risk.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Miller |first1=Laura J. |title=Psychotic Denial of Pregnancy: Phenomenology and Clinical Management |journal=Psychiatric Services |volume=41 |issue=11 |pages=1233–7 |year=1990 |pmid=2249803 |doi=10.1176/ps.41.11.1233 }}</ref>

