{{About|the modern new religious movement|the Iron Age magico-religious specialists|Druid}}
[[File:Druids celebrating at Stonehenge (1).png|thumb|upright=1.35|A group of Druids at [[Stonehenge]] in [[Wiltshire]], [[England]]]]
[[File:GorseddDigorHanvec1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|The Great Druid of France [[Gwenc'hlan Le Scouëzec]] stands at the centre surrounded by the Archdruid of Wales and the Great Bardess of Cornwall, at the celebration of the hundredth anniversary of the [[Goursez Vreizh|Gorseth of Brittany]] in [[Hanvec]], year 1999.]]
'''Druidry''', sometimes termed '''Druidism''', is a modern [[spirituality|spiritual]] or [[religion|religious]] movement that generally promotes harmony, connection, and reverence for the natural world. This commonly is extended to include respect for all beings, including the environment itself. Many forms of modern Druidry are [[modern Paganism|modern Pagan]] religions, although most of the earliest modern Druids identified as [[Christianity|Christians]]. Originating in Britain during the 18th century, Druidry was originally a cultural movement, only gaining religious or spiritual connotations in the 19th century.

The core principle of Druidry is respect and veneration of nature, and as such it often involves participation in the [[environmentalism|environmental movement]]. Another prominent belief among modern Druids is the veneration of ancestors, particularly those who belonged to prehistoric societies.

Arising from the 18th century [[Romanticism|Romanticist movement]] in Britain, which glorified the ancient [[Celts|Celtic]] peoples of the [[British Iron Age|Iron Age]], the early neo-Druids aimed to imitate the Iron Age priests who were also known as [[druid]]s. At the time, little accurate information was known about these ancient priests, and the modern Druidic movement has no direct connection to them, despite contrary claims made by some modern Druids.<ref name="britishmuseum">{{cite web |quote=Modern Druids have no direct connection to the Druids of the Iron Age. Many of our popular ideas about the Druids are based on the misunderstandings and misconceptions of scholars 200 years ago. These ideas have been superseded by later study and discoveries. |url=http://www.thebritishmuseum.ac.uk/explore/highlights/article_index/d/the_druids.aspx |publisher=The British Museum |title=The Druids |accessdate=1 December 2014}}</ref>

In the late 18th century, modern Druids developed fraternal organizations modeled on [[Freemasonry]] that employed the romantic figure of the British Druids and [[Bard|Bards]] as symbols of indigenous British spirituality. Some of these groups were purely fraternal and cultural, creating traditions from the national imagination of Britain. Others, in the early 20th century, merged with contemporary movements such as the [[physical culture]] movement and [[naturism]]. Since the 1980s, some modern druid groups have adopted similar methodologies to those of [[Celtic Reconstructionist Paganism]] in an effort to create a more historically accurate practice. However, there is still controversy over how much resemblance modern Druidism may or may not have to the Iron Age druids.

==Definition==

[[File:An Arch Druid in His Judicial Habit.jpg|thumb|Modern Druidry takes its name from the Iron Age druids referred to in various Greco-Roman sources, as depicted here in a nineteenth-century illustration.]]

Modern Druidry derives its name from the magico-religious specialists of Iron Age Western Europe who were known as [[druids]].{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=351}} There is no real historical continuity between the druids of Iron Age Europe and the modern Druids.{{sfnm|1a1=Butler|1y=2005|1p=94|2a1=Doyle White|2y=2016|2p=351}} However, some Druids nevertheless regard modern Druidry as a genuine continuation of the practices of the Iron Age druids.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=88}} The concerns of modern Druidry—which include healing the planet and seeking connections with the natural world—are likely very different from those of the Iron Age societies in which the original druids lived.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=96}}

Everything presently known about the Iron Age druids derives from archaeological evidence and Greco-Roman textual sources, rather than material produced by these druids themselves.{{sfn|Cooper|2009b|pp=41–42}} Due to the scarcity of knowledge about the Iron Age druids, their belief system cannot be accurately reconstructed.{{sfn|Butler|2005|pp=94–95}} Some Druids incorporate everything that is known about Iron Age druids into their practices.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=97}} However, as noted by scholar of religion Jenny Butler, the historical realities of Iron Age religion are often overlooked by Druids in favour of "a highly romanticised version".{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=96}}
Many Druids believe that the practices of the Iron Age druids should be revived yet modified to meet current needs.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=91}}
In Ireland, some Druids have claimed that because the island was never conquered by the [[Roman Empire]], here the Iron Age druids survived and their teachings were passed down hereditarily until modern times, at which modern Druids can reclaim them.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=92}} Some Druids claim that they can [[Mediumship#Channeling|channel]] information about the Iron Age druids.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=93}}

Druidry has been described as a religion,{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=59}} a [[new religious movement]],{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=60}} a "spiritual movement",{{sfn|Gieser|2016|p=55}} and as a [[nature religion]].{{sfn|Gieser|2016|p=55}} It has been described as a form of contemporary Paganism,{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=59}} and on the contemporary Pagan spectrum between reconstructionism and eclecticism, Druidry sits on the latter end.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=348}} Various Druidic groups also display [[New Age]] and [[Neo-shamanism|neo-shamanic]] influences.{{sfn|Anczyk|2015|p=20}}
The Druidic community has been characterised as a [[Neotribalism|neo-tribe]], for it is disembedded and its membership is elective.{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=25}}
Druidry has been described as a form of [[Celtic spirituality]],{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=78}} or "Celtic-Based Spirituality".{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=87}} Scholar of religion Marion Bowman described Druidry as the "Celtic spirituality ''par excellence''.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=78}} Some practitioners regard Druidry as a form of "native spirituality",{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=83}} and it displays an affinity with [[folk religion]]s.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=59}}
In defining Druidry as a "native spirituality", some Druids seek to draw elements from other [[native religions]], such as the belief systems of Australian Aboriginal and Native American communities.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=83}} Practitioners differ in the levels of formality and seriousness that they bring to their adherence.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=82}} Some groups use the word ''Druid'' for both male and female practitioners, eschewing the term ''Druidess'' for female followers.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=103}}

[[File:Druid Order Spring Equinox Ceremony Tower Hill 2010.JPG|thumb|left|The Druid Order Ceremony at Tower Hill, London on the Spring Equinox of 2010]]

Following terms devised by the Druid [[Philip Carr-Gomm]], a distinction has been drawn between "cultural" Druids, who adopt the term as part of their Welsh and Cornish cultural activities, and "esoteric" Druids who pursue the movement as a religion.{{sfnm|1a1=Hale|1y=2000|1p=189|2a1=Bowman|2y=2002|2p=79}} The scholar of religion Marion Bowman suggested "believing" as an alternative term to "esoteric".{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=79}} There are also individuals who cross these two categories, involving themselves in cultural Druidic events while also holding to modern Pagan beliefs.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=79}} Some cultural Druids nevertheless go to efforts to disassociate themselves from their esoteric and Pagan counterpart; the [[Cornish Gorseth]] for example has publicly disassociated any links to Paganism.{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=189}}
Some Druids identify as Pagan, others as Christian.{{sfnm|1a1=Bowman|1y=2002|1p=82|2a1=Butler|2y=2005|2p=88}} Some practitioners merge Pagan and Christian elements in their own personal practice,{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=88}} in at least one case identifying as a "Christodruid".{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=63}} Other practitioners adopt additional elements; for instance there are self-described "[[Zen Buddhism|Zen]] Druids" and "[[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic]] Druids".{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=82}} The Berengia Order of Druids drew upon elements from [[science fiction]] television shows like ''[[Star Trek]]'' and ''[[Babylon 5]]''.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=82}}

The earliest modern Druids aligned themselves with Christianity.{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=188}}
In the early eighteenth-century, early Druidic writers like [[William Stukeley]] regarded the Iron Age druids as proto-Christians who were monotheists worshipping the Christian God.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=85}} In a similar vein, some modern Druids believe that ancient druidic wisdom was preserved through a distinct [[Celtic Christianity]].{{sfn|Bowman|2002|pp=85–86}} Over the course of the twentieth century, and particularly since the early 1960s, Druidry increasingly came to be associated with the modern Pagan movement.{{sfn|Hale|2000|pp=188–189}}

==Beliefs==
[[File:Tribann.svg|thumb|upright=0.7|The [[Awen]] symbol of [[Iolo Morganwg]].]]
Druidic beliefs vary widely, and there is no set dogma or belief system followed by all adherents.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=30}}

Druidry also draws upon the legends surrounding [[King Arthur]].{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=193}} One of the clearest links between Arthuriana and Druidry is through the [[Loyal Arthurian Warband]], a Druidic group that employs Arthurian symbolism as part of its environmental campaigns.{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=193}}

===Nature-centered spirituality===

Druidry has been described as a nature venerating movement.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=60}}
Druidry conceives of the natural world as being imbued with spirit, and thus regard it as alive and dynamic.{{sfn|Gieser|2016|p=63}}
Because they view the natural world as sacred, many Druids are involved in [[environmentalism]], thereby acting to protect areas of the natural landscape that are under threat from development or pollution.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|pp=31–32}}

Druids are generally critical of mainstream society, regarding it as being "governed by consumerism, environmental exploitation and the supremacy of technology."{{sfn|Gieser|2016|p=62}} In contrast to this, Druids seek to establish a way of living that they regard as being more "natural".{{sfn|Gieser|2016|p=62}} Through seeking a connection with nature, Druids pursue a sense of "cosmic belonging".{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=68}}

===Theology===

{{Quote box|width=246px|align=right|quote="Grant O Goddess, thy protection<br/>and in protection, strength<br/>and in strength, understanding<br/>and in understanding, knowledge<br/>and in knowledge, the knowledge of justice<br/>and in the knowledge of justice, the love of it<br/>and in the love of it, the love of all existences<br/>and in the love of all existences, the love of Goddess and all Goodness"|source="The Druid's Prayer", after Iolo Morganwg.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=30}} }}

By the end of the 19th century, Druidry was described as a "monotheistic philosophical tradition".<ref>[[#Har07|Harvey 2007]]. p. 34.</ref> 
Druidry is now often described as [[polytheism|polytheistic]],{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=60}} although there is no set pantheon of deities to which all Druids adhere.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=68}} Emphasis is however placed on the idea that these deities predate Christianity.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=70}} These deities are usually regarded as being immanent rather than transcendent.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=69}} Some practitioners express the view that the real existence of these deities is less important to them than the impact that said belief has on their lives.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=69}}

With the increase in polytheistic Druidry, and the widespread acceptance of Goddess worship, "The Druid's Prayer", which had been originally written in the 18th century by Druid [[Iolo Morganwg]] and emphasises the unity of the supreme Deity, had the word "God" replaced with "Goddess" in common usage.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=30}}

Some Druids regard it as possible to communicate with various spirits during ritual.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=105}} Certain Druids in Ireland have for instance adopted belief in the [[Aos Sí|Sí]], spirits from Irish folklore, into their Druidic system, interpreting them as [[elementals]].{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=104}} They have adopted the folkloric belief that such spirits are repelled by iron and thus avoid bringing iron to their rituals, so as not to scare spirits away.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=105}}

====Awen====
{{Main|Awen}}
Awen is a concept of spirit or divinity in Druidry,{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=189}} which inspires poetry and art, and is believed to be a "flowing spirit" given by the Deity, which can be invoked by the Druid.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=20}} In many Druidic rituals, Awen is invoked by either chanting the word "Awen" or "A-I-O" three times, in order to shift the consciousness of the participants involved.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=21}} The word "Awen" derives from the Welsh and Cornish terms for "inspiration".{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=189}}

===Ancestor veneration===

A connection with ancestors is important in Druidry.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=71}} In some recorded examples, Druids regard the "ancestors" as an amorphous group, rather than as a set of named individuals.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=355}} The Druidic concept of ancestry is that of "ancestors of the land", rather than the "ancestors of the blood" venerated by some Heathen groups; they perceive a spiritual connection, rather than a genetic one, as being important.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=355}} Emphasising ancestors gives practitioners a sense of an identity which has been passed down from the past over the course of many centuries.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=71}}

Ancestor veneration leads many to object to the [[archaeology|archaeological]] excavation of [[Cadaver|human remains]] and their subsequent display in museums. Many have organised campaigns for their [[Repatriation and reburial of human remains|reburial]]. For instance, in 2006, a neo-Druid called Paul Davies requested that the Alexander Keiller Museum in [[Avebury]], [[Wiltshire]] rebury their human remains, and that storing and displaying them was "immoral and disrespectful".<ref>{{cite journal |title=Consultation on ancient human remains ends Jan 31 |journal=British Archaeology |issue=104 |year=2009}}</ref> Criticism of this view has come from the archaeological community, with statements like "no single modern ethnic group or cult should be allowed to appropriate our ancestors for their own agendas. It is for the international scientific community to curate such remains."<ref>{{cite journal |title=Letters: Human Remains |journal=British Archaeology |issue=105 |year=2009}}</ref>

==Rites and practices==

Druidic groups are usually known as ''groves''.{{sfnm|1a1=Butler|1y=2005|1p=90|2a1=Harvey|2y=2007|2p=29}} Such a term reflects the movement's association with trees,{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=90}} and references the idea that Iron Age druids performed their rituals within tree groves.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=91}} Larger Druidic organisations are usually termed ''orders'',{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=29}} and those that lead them are often termed ''chosen chiefs''.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=32}}

Some British Druid orders divide membership into three grades, referred to as "bards", "ovates", and then "Druids".{{sfnm|1a1=Letcher|1y=2004|1p=24|2a1=Harvey|2y=2007|2p=32}} This three-tier system mirrors the three degrees found in [[British Traditional Wicca]].{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=24}} Other groups eschew any division into bard, ovate, and druid.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|pp=19–20}} OBOD primarily educates its members in its form of Druidry through a correspondence course.{{sfn|Anczyk|2015|p=17}}

===Ceremonies===
[[File:Druids, in the early morning glow of the sun.jpg|thumb|right|A group of druids of the Order of Bards Ovates and Druids in the early morning glow of the sun, shortly after having welcomed the sunrise at Stonehenge on the morning of the summer solstice.]]

Each Druidic grove conducts its rituals and ceremonies in a unique way.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=88}} Druidic rituals are designed to align their participants with the spirit imbuing nature.{{sfn|Gieser|2016|p=63}} According to the anthropologist Thorsten Gieser, Druidic rituals are best seen not as a set of formalised actions but as "a stance, an attitude, a particular mode of experience and perception which gives rise to a feeling of being-in-the-world, of being part of Nature."{{sfn|Gieser|2016|p=63}}
The practices of modern Druids typically take place outside, in the daylight, in what is described as "the eye of the sun", meaning around midday.{{sfnm|1a1=Bowman|1y=2002|1p=81|2a1=Harvey|2y=2007|2p=20}} In some cases, they instead perform their rites indoors, or during the night.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=20}} Druidic rituals usually reflect on the time of year and the changing of the seasons.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}}

Druidic rituals often involve the participants standing in a circle and begin with a "calling of the quarters", in which a participant draws a circle in the air in a deosil direction to hail the north, south, east, and west, marking out the space in which the ceremony will take place.{{sfnm|1a1=Butler|1y=2005|1p=109|2a1=Doyle White|2y=2016|2pp=361–362}} Libations may be poured onto the ground while a chalice of drink is passed around the assembled participants, again in a deosil direction. Food, often in the form of bread or cake, is also passed around the Druids and consumed.{{sfnm|1a1=Butler|1y=2005|1pp=109–110|2a1=Doyle White|2y=2016|2p=362}} This may be followed by a period of meditation among those assembled.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=110}} A form of earth energy is then visualised, with participants believing that it is sent for a designated healing purpose.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=110}} This may be designed to help the victims of a particular event, such as a war or an epidemic, or it might be directed to assist individuals known to the group who are ill or requiring emotional support.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=112}} After the end of the ceremony, the Druids may remain together to take part in a meal,{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=111}} or visit a nearby [[pub]].{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=362}}

There is no specific dress code for ritual within the Druidic movement; some participants wear ordinary clothes, others wear robes.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}} Some groups favour earth-coloured robes, believing that this links them to the natural world and that it aids them in traveling unnoticed when going about at night.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=93}} "Celtish" language is often employed during ceremonies,{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}} as are quotations and material from the ''[[Carmina Gadelica]]''.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}} Most use some form of Morganwg's Gorsedd Prayer.{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=189}}

Some Druids also involve themselves in spell-casting, although this is usually regarded as a secondary feature among their practices.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=112}}

====Locations for ritual====

Rituals commonly take place at formations in the natural landscape or at prehistoric sites, among them [[megalith]]ic constructions from the Neolithic and Bronze Age or earthworks from the Iron Age.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=96}} Druids often believe that, even if the Iron Age druids did not build these monuments, they did use them for their rites.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=97}} Performing rituals at said sites allows many Druids to feel that they are getting close to their ancestors.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=98}} Druids regard them as [[sacred sites]] in part as recognition that prehistoric societies would have done the same.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=358}}
Druids in various parts of Ireland and Britain have reported such sites being home to a "Spirit of the Place" residing there.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=358}}
Many Druids also believe that such sites are centres of [[Energy (esotericism)|earth energy]] and lie along [[ley lines]] in the landscape.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=356}} These are ideas that have been adopted from [[Earth mysteries]] writers like [[John Michell (writer)|John Michell]].{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=357}}

[[File:Druids celebrating at Stonehenge (0).png|thumb|left|upright=1.15|Druidic ritual at Stonehenge in Wiltshire, southern England]]

In the popular imagination, Druids are closely linked with [[Stonehenge]]—a Neolithic and Bronze Age site in [[Wiltshire]], southern England.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=80}} Although Stonehenge predates the Iron Age and there is no evidence that it was ever used by Iron Age druids, many modern Druids believe that their ancient namesakes did indeed use it for their ceremonies.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=80}} Druids also use many other prehistoric sites as spaces for their rituals, including [[Stone circles in the British Isles and Brittany|stone circles]] like that at [[Avebury]] in Wiltshire.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}} Some Druids have erected their own, modern stone circles in which to perform their ceremonies.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=106}} 
Druidic practices have also taken place at Early Neolithic [[chambered long barrow]]s such as [[Wayland's Smithy]] in [[Oxfordshire]],{{sfn|Gieser|2016|pp=60–61, 64, 67}} and the [[Coldrum Long Barrow]] in [[Kent]].{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=349}}
In Ireland, Druids perform ceremonies at one of the island's best known prehistoric sites, the [[Hill of Tara]].{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=95}} In 2000, scholar of religion Amy Hale noted that Druidic rituals at such prehistoric sites were "increasingly more common".{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=192}} She regarded the stone circle as "a symbol of an imagined Celtic past" shared by both Druids and Gorseth Bards.{{sfn|Hale|2000|p=193}} As well as performing group rituals at sites, Druids also visit them alone to meditate, prayer, and provide offerings.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=360}} Aside from Sabbat rituals, [[rites of passage]] can also take place at such sites, such as a Druidic baby-naming ceremony which took place at Kent's [[Chestnuts Long Barrow]].{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=363}}

Attitudes to land and environmental conservation are important to the Druidic world-view.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=114}} 
In 2003, Druids performed a ritual at the Hill of Tara to heal the location after road construction took place in the adjacent landscape.{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=95}} Others have carried out rituals at Coldrum Long Barrow to oppose [[fracking]] in the landscape.{{sfn|Doyle White|2016|p=368}} Druids have also involved themselves in tree planting projects.{{sfn|Butler|2005|pp=121–122}}

In the 1990s and early 2000s, the use of a ritual based on the [[sweat lodge]] became increasingly popular among some Neo-druids in Ireland and the U.K.{{sfnm|1a1=Bowman|1y=2002|1p=83|2a1=Harvey|2y=2007|2pp=26–27}} Some Druids regard these sweat lodges as "initiatory and regenerative opportunities to rededicate oneself to honouring the Earth and the community of life."{{sfn|Harvey|2007|pp=26–27}} This practice is regarded differently by different individuals. Some practitioners regard it as a "revival" of genuine pre-Christian druidic practices, others see it a creative and respectful borrowing from one "native spirituality" into another, and a third school of thought regards it as a form of cultural theft.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=83}} Native Americans who preserve the sweat lodge ceremonies for their communities have protested the appropriation of the ceremony by non-Natives,<ref name="Taliman2">{{citation | first = Valerie |last = Taliman | title = Selling the sacred | publisher = Indian Country Today | url = http://indiancountrytodaymedianetwork.com/ict_sbc/selling-the-sacred | date=13 October 2009}}</ref> increasingly so now that people have been injured, and some have [[Sweat lodge#Risks|died]], in fraudulent [[sweat lodge]] ceremonies performed by non-Natives.<ref name="Taliman2"/><ref name="Dehydration and heat-related death">{{cite news|first=RW|last=Byard|work=Forensic Science SA|title=Dehydration and heat-related death: sweat lodge syndrome|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=Retrieve&db=PubMed&list_uids=16121078&dopt=Abstract|date=2005-09-26|accessdate=2006-09-26}}</ref><ref name="2 die in new-age sweat lodge">{{cite news|first=Suzanne|last=Herel|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]|title=2 seeking spiritual enlightenment die in new-age sweat lodge|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2002/06/27/BA212763.DTL|date=2002-06-27|accessdate=2006-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | first = Bob |last = Goulais | title = Editorial: Dying to experience native ceremonies | newspaper = North Bay Nugget | date = 2009-10-24 | url =http://www.nugget.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=2144903}}</ref><ref>Hocker, Lindsay. [http://qconline.com/archives/qco/display.php?id=462433 "Sweat lodge incident 'not our Indian way'"], ''Quad-Cities Online'', 14 October 2009.</ref>

===Arts and poetry===

[[File:ArthurPendragonStonehengeSummerSolstice2010.jpg|thumb|right|Arthur Uther Pendragon attending 2010 Summer Solstice ceremony at Stonehenge.]]

In Druidry, a specific ceremony takes place known as an ''[[Eisteddfod]]'', which is dedicated to the recitation of poetry and musical performances.{{sfnm|1a1=Letcher|1y=2004|1pp=16–17|2a1=Harvey|2y=2007|2p=22}} Within the Druidic community, practitioners who are particularly skilled in their recitation of poetry or their performance of music are referred to as Bards.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=20}} Although bardism can also be found in other Pagan traditions such as [[Eco-Paganism]], it is of particular importance within Druidry.{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=16}} Bards perform at ''Eisteddfod'' at various occasions, from formal rituals to pub get-togethers and summer camps and environmental protests.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=22}} Among the Druidic community, it is often believed that bards should be divinely inspired in producing their work.{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=17}}

Storytelling is important within Druidry,{{sfn|Butler|2005|p=121}} with stories chosen often coming from the vernacular literature of linguistically Celtic countries or from Arthurian legend.{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=16}} Musical performances typically draw from the folk musical traditions of [[Irish traditional music|Ireland]], [[Scottish folk music|Scotland]], [[Folk music of England|England]], [[French folk music|France]], and [[Music of Brittany#Traditional Breton music|Brittany]].{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=16}} 
Instruments used commonly include [[lap harp]]s, [[mandolin]]s, [[whistle]]s, [[bag pipes]], and [[guitar]]s.{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=16}} Bards utilise archaic words such as "t'was", "thence", and "deeds", while speaking in a grandiose manner of intonation.{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=16}} The general purpose of bardism, according to scholar of religion and bard Andy Letcher, is to create an "ambience" of "a catchall ahistorical past; a Celtic, medieval, Tolkienesque, once-upon-a-time enchanted world".{{sfn|Letcher|2004|p=16}} Instruments commonly used by Druidic Bards include acoustic stringed instruments like the guitar and the [[clarsach]], as well as the [[bodhran]], bagpipe, rattle, flute and whistle. The scholar of religion Graham Harvey believed that these specific instruments were preferred by modern Druids because many of them were Irish in origin, and therefore gave a "Celtic flavour, seemingly invoking the Iron Age", the period during which the ancient druids lived.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=22}}

Groups like the [[British Druid Order]] have established their own ''[[gorseddau]]''.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}} Unlike the Welsh cultural gorseddau, these Druidic events often allow anyone to perform as a bard if they are inspired to do so.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}}

Druids have participated in other musical genres and with more technological instruments, including the [[blues]] and [[rave]] music, and one British club, Megatripolis, opened with the performance of a Druidic ritual.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|pp=23–24}}

===Other practices===
[[File:Druidess.png|thumb|A female Druid at Stonehenge]]

Among many Druids, there is a system of tree lore, through which different associations are attributed to different species of tree, including particular moods, actions, phases of life, deities and ancestors.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=25}} Different species of trees are often linked to the [[ogham]] alphabet, which is employed in divination by Druids.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=25}} Rather than ogham, some practitioners favour [[Coelbren y Beirdd|coelbren]]—an alphabet likely devised by [[Iolo Morganwg]]—for their divinatory practices.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=26}}

Many Druids engage in a range of healing therapies, with both [[herbalism]] and [[homeopathy]] being popular within the Druidic community.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=26}}

Druids often revive older folk customs for use on their practices.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=203}} The England-based Secular Order of Druids for instance possess a [[hobby horse]] based on that used in the [['Obby 'Oss festival]] of [[Padstow]], [[Cornwall]].{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=23}}

===Festivals===
Druids generally observe eight spiritual festivals annually, which are collectively known as the [[Wheel of the Year]].{{sfnm|1a1=Bowman|1y=2002|1p=81|2a1=Butler|2y=2005|2p=108|3a1=Cooper|3y=2009|3p=66}} These are the same festivals usually celebrated by Wiccans.{{sfn|Cooper|2009|p=66}} In some cases groups attempt to revive folkloric European festivals and their accompanying traditions.{{sfn|Harvey|2007|p=23}} In other cases the rites are modern inventions, inspired by "the spirit of what they believe was the religious practice of pre-Roman Britain."<ref name=Gallagher>{{Cite book | last1 = Gallagher | first1 = Eugene V. | last2 = Ashcraft | first2 = W. Michael | title = Introduction to new and alternative religions in America | year = 2006 | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = Westport, Conn. | isbn = 978-0-275-98713-8 | pages = 178 }}</ref> For reasons of practicality, such celebrations are not always held on the specific date of the festival itself, but on the nearest weekend, thus maximising the number of participants who can attend.{{sfn|Bowman|2002|p=81}}

Four of these are solar festivals, being positioned at the solstices and equinoxes; these are largely inspired by [[Germanic paganism]]. The other four are the "[[Celts|Celtic]]" festivals, the crossquarter days inspired by modern interpretations of ancient [[Celtic polytheism]]. The idea of the Wheel of the Year was introduced into Druidry by [[Ross Nichols]], who founded the [[Order of Bards, Ovates and Druids]] in 1964, and he had gained this idea from his friend [[Gerald Gardner (Wiccan)|Gerald Gardner]], who had implemented it in his [[Bricket Wood coven]] of [[Gardnerian Wicca|Gardnerian Witches]] in 1958.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}

